</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Jasin Zujovic &lt;jzujo...@inet.hr&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-10-04T14:33:00 </POSTDATE>
I was just looking through my characters folder today and I've gotten
kind of nostalgic for all these characters I'll probably never play now
that 4E's coming out.

So lets share characters we wanted to play at one time but never got
around to it (or never got around to playing them to your satisfaction).

My first 3E character was a spirit folk martial artist/shaman/blade
dancer, looking for his ranger/shugenja/witch hunter friend which went
missing while looking for an evil monk/tattooed monk (planning to take
Leadership once he found her). The first session, the DM got annoyed
with another player and TPK-ed us to prove a point. Jackass.

I have a gnome bard 11/paladin 2 with Devoted Pefromer and Arcane Strike
and a wand of divine power. Imagine saying &quot;I'm a gnome bard!&quot; and then
charging into melee to Arcane Strike Power Attack smite someone for
massive damage!

Sister Ariana was a longsword-wielding cleric 6/monk 1, going for
loremaster. Another wuxia wandering swordsman type, and another
character where a big part of the appeal is surprising those who
underestimate you based on your appearance and the fact that you took
Skill Focus in a knowledge.

Togashi Toshi was a Tamori yamabushi in a Rokugan campaign that lasted
for just a session or two. I used a &quot;battle shugenja&quot;: UA battle
sorcerer tweaks applied to a shugenja rather than a sorcerer. A nother
sort of wuxia type: I took Versatile from rokugan to get jump and tumble
as class skills, and Leap of the Heavens, Acrobatic Strike and Leap
Attack. He was one of the most satisfying warrior-mages I played.

There's also a rogue/cleric/shadowbane stalker with a mercurial
greatsword, a Mercykiller for a Planescape game. Think Severian meets
Dark Justice guy. A nice, quiet kind of guy... unless you're GUILTY, in
which case he's the masked, black-plated, black-cloaked figure you see
with the corner of your eye just before the executioner's sword comes
arcing down.

So, what about yours?

--
Jasin
