It was.  This was a sort of &quot;special occasion&quot; game, where a bunch of us
(from the Sacramento area) were traveling to the Bay Area to play with old
friends from that area that do not play often.  I was expecting the party to
be more or less &quot;standard race/class&quot; D&amp;D, but it ended up being a bit of a
menagerie of weirdness.  For one, I figured I was going to be the &quot;token big
guy tank.&quot;  Turns out we had two.  Here is the party break down (everyone is
1st level, being played for the first time, and male unless noted):

Goliath Warblade (Goliath Greathammer) - described a bit above
Half-Ogre Fighter (Large Greataxe) - typical &quot;big dumb fighter&quot;
Tiefling Wizard - played like a somewhat perverted, effeminate used car
salesman
Halfling Rogue (female, played before) - a typical &quot;thief&quot; character,
avoiding combat as much as possible, and trying to sneak loot without anyone
finding out
Human Cleric of Wee Jas - played a little too &quot;over the top&quot; evil, 2nd level
Aasimar Monk (Vow of Poverty) - high AC build, slightly paladin-like
attitude
Aasimar Spirit Shaman - player was pretty quiet
Aasimar Cleric of Pelor - future Radiant Servant, player was pretty quiet

The plot was a infiltration into a Hobgoblin slave camp (the slavers were
associated with Iuz).  The Wizard and the two tanks were a slaver and two
bodyguards, respectively, and the rest were posing as slaves, but had
daggers enchanted to be invisible for a few days, or until used.  The real
slaves were to banged up and demoralized to be of much use.  There was a lot
of fun with the roleplaying, especially with the low Charisma Wizard running
the show (he decided that his low Charisma was due to him having a creepy,
slimy personality).  He haggled over the price of the slaves he was selling,
claiming that since he had &quot;sweet, juicy celestials,&quot; he should get double
what they were offering.  My Goliath got to save the Half-Ogre's life ealier
in the adventure, and I reminded him of our 1-0 score for the rest of the
game, which got some laughs.  We also had intra-party violence twice.  The
Wizard cast Burning Hands on the Rogue, because she stole his pack with all
his money (it was so heavy that the encumbrance penalty messed up her
theft).  That made his point, and she gave up.  The Cleric of Wee Jas, for
some inexplicable reason, decided to kill one of the slaves &quot;as a
distraction,&quot; and was caught by the Monk, who proceded to beat him
unconscious, and hand him over to the elves at the end of the adventure.

