Thought of more:

Jakari, a barbarian tribeswoman turned gladiator turned pirate
captain. She was an NPC in a campaign some years back, and lots of fun
to play, especially when she became attracted to one of the PCs, who
was exactly the same kind of hard-boiled survivor that she was.

Kleig, a firbolg that left his clan to find a way to lift a curse that
is slowly turning the other firbolgs into trees. This guy dates back
to the 2e Humanoids Handbook, when I was trying to think of a reason
why a reclusive giant-kin would be out adventuring. He was scared to
death of humans due to &quot;giant-killer&quot; stories he'd heard as a boy (re-
cast as lessons in good behavior for young giants - &quot;Mind ye manners,
boy, or Tiny Jack will come through the floor and cut off your toes
while you sleep!&quot;). He had nightmares about humans' little hands,
little teeth, and shrill little voices.

Fizgug, a mongrelfolk rogue that I actually played for a while in a 2e
Ravenloft campaign.  Always wanted to update him for 3.x and have
another go. He was raised as an &quot;Igor-esque&quot; slave to an evil wizard
who ended up getting killed by noble adventurer types, forcing Fizgug
to make his own way in the world. Very resourceful and clever, but
uncomfortable with independence, he kept latching on to other PCs as
his new &quot;masters.&quot;

